Customer Feedback/Reviews - Lego on Amazon.com¶

The focus of this project is to find meaningful insights into popular LEGO products using customer reviews sourced from Amazon. The target audience would include LEGO enthusiasts, toy businesses, and marketers looking for consumer preferences and market trends in the LEGO industry.

Purpose of Analysis¶

This analysis aims to:

  • Guide LEGO fans in finding the most loved products.(Budget between 50 to 150.)
  • Providing valuable insights into customer sentiment and product performance to business owners.
  • Support marketers in refining their campaigns based on the analysis of sentiment and review trends.
  • In leveraging such data, this study intends to empower strategic decision-making of key stakeholders in the LEGO marketplace.

Business Questions¶

A number of key business questions can be identified based on the developed dataset, such as the following:

  • What is the distribution of the overall rating?
  • Which dates have the highest number of reviews?
  • What are the common themes found in the reviews?
  • Which LEGO products were highest rated?
  • What is the average rating of LEGO sets in different periods?
  • Who are the most active reviewers?
  • What is the proportion of very positive or negative reviews?

#Get Chrome driver
from selenium.webdriver.firefox.options import Options

options = Options()
options.add_argument('--disable-blink-features=AutomationControlled')

driver = webdriver.Chrome(options=options)

Part 1: Web Scrapping from Amazon.com¶

  1. Brand: LEGO
  2. Price Range: US 50-150
  3. Age Range: 14 Years and UP
In [50]:
reviews_dic = {'Product': [], 'Price': [], 'Customer': [], 'Ratings': [], 'Date': [], 'Review_text': []}

driver.implicitly_wait(10)

for index, new_link in enumerate(new_review_links[:5]):

    product_name = product_df.iloc[index]['Product']
    product_price = product_df.iloc[index]['Price']
    
    driver.get(new_link)
    time.sleep(10)
    
    # Find all elements that match the XPath
    names = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-profile-name"]')
    ratings = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-size-base a-link-normal review-title a-color-base review-title-content a-text-bold"]/i/span')
    dates = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-size-base a-color-secondary review-date"]')
    reviews = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-expander-content reviewText review-text-content a-expander-partial-collapse-content"]/span') 
    
    # Iterate over each element to get its text content
    for name, rating, date, review in zip(names, ratings, dates, reviews):
        reviews_dic["Product"].append(product_name) 
        reviews_dic["Price"].append(product_price)  
        reviews_dic["Customer"].append(name.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Ratings'].append(rating.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Date'].append(date.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Review_text'].append(review.get_attribute('textContent').strip())

print("Data collection is done!")

Data collection is done!

# Initialize an empty list to store updated links
new_review_links = []

# Loop through each review link in the product_df
for link in filtered_df1["Review_url"]:
    
    # Split the link to remove the query parameters and session ID, if any
    base_link = link.split('/ref=')[0]
    session_id = link.split('/')[-1]
    
    # For each link, generate new links for each pageNumber in the range
    for i in range(1, 6):  # Generates 5 new URLs per original URL
        # Construct the new link with the updated ref part and append "?pageNumber=i"
        # example url:
        # {https://www.amazon.com/product-reviews/B0CP9Z56SW}/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_paging_btm_next_{2}/{140-2291549-5442769}?pageNumber={2}
        
        new_link = f"{base_link}/ref=zg_bs_g_kitchen_d_sccl_{i}_cr/{session_id}?pageNumber={i}"
        new_review_links.append(new_link)

        
# Now, new_review_links contains all the modified links
for new_link in new_review_links:
    print(new_link)

In [80]:
reviews_dic = {'Product_url':[], 'Customer': [], 'Ratings': [], 'Date': [], 'Review_text': []}

driver.implicitly_wait(10)

for new_link in new_review_links:
    driver.get(new_link)
    time.sleep(10)
    
    # Find all elements that match the XPath
    names = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-profile-name"]')
    ratings = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-size-base a-link-normal review-title a-color-base review-title-content a-text-bold"]/i/span')
    dates = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-size-base a-color-secondary review-date"]')
    reviews = driver.find_elements("xpath", '//*[@class="a-expander-content reviewText review-text-content a-expander-partial-collapse-content"]/span') 
    product_urls = driver.find_element("xpath", '//*[@id="a-page"]/link[2]')
    
    # Iterate over each element to get its text content
    for name, rating, date, review in zip(names,ratings,dates,reviews):
        reviews_dic["Customer"].append(name.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Ratings'].append(rating.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Date'].append(date.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Review_text'].append(review.get_attribute('textContent').strip())
        reviews_dic['Product_url'].append(product_urls.get_attribute('href'))
        
print("Data collection is done!")

Data collection is done!

# define the parts of speech function
from nltk.tag import pos_tag
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer

# Initialize lemmatizer
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def nouns_adjs(text):
    text = text.lower()
    token_list = word_tokenize(text)
    
    # unwanted words set
    remove_words = {'t', 'vse', 'i', 'review', 'com', 'didn','don'}
    clean_text = [word for word in token_list if word not in remove_words]
    
    # label the parts of speech
    word_tag = pos_tag(clean_text)
    nouns_adjs_lists = [word for word, tag in word_tag if tag in ["NN", "NNP", "NNS", "JJ", "JJR", "JJS"]]
    
    # lemmatizing the nouns and adjectives
    lemma_words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in nouns_adjs_lists]

    nouns_adjs = ' '.join(lemma_words)
    
    return nouns_adjs
In [118]:
# import the data and seperate the product reviews by the product name
# filter all the nouns and adjectives

reviews_df["Nouns_adjs"] = reviews_df["Review_text"].apply(nouns_adjs)

import re 

def clean_date(date_string):
    match = re.search(r'on ([a-zA-Z]+ \d{1,2}, \d{4})', date_string)
    if match:
        return pd.to_datetime(match.group(1), format='%B %d, %Y')
    return None  

reviews_df['Cleaned_Date'] = reviews_df['Date'].apply(clean_date)
reviews_df['Year'] = reviews_df['Cleaned_Date'].dt.year

7. What is the proportion of very positive or negative reviews?¶

In [156]:
# Define thresholds for very positive and very negative reviews
positive_threshold = 4.5
negative_threshold = 2.5

# Filter very positive and very negative reviews
very_positive = review_df[review_df['Ratings'] >= positive_threshold]
very_negative = review_df[review_df['Ratings'] <= negative_threshold]

# Calculate proportions
total_reviews = len(reviews_df)
proportion_positive = len(very_positive) / total_reviews * 100
proportion_negative = len(very_negative) / total_reviews * 100

# Display the results
print(f"Proportion of Very Positive Reviews: {proportion_positive:.2f}%")
print(f"Proportion of Very Negative Reviews: {proportion_negative:.2f}%")

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer

Method 1: sklearn NMF model¶

In [159]:
from sklearn.decomposition import NMF
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline

# Replace NaN values in the "Nouns_adjs" column with an empty string
review_df["Nouns_adjs"] = review_df["Nouns_adjs"].fillna("")

# Set up the topic modeling pipeline using NMF
nmf_model = make_pipeline(
    TfidfVectorizer(),
    NMF(n_components=10, random_state=0, init="nndsvd")
)

# Train the model using the preprocessed data
NMF_result = nmf_model.fit_transform(review_df["Nouns_adjs"])

# Extract components and feature names
nmf = nmf_model.named_steps['nmf']
tfidf = nmf_model.named_steps['tfidfvectorizer']
feature_names = tfidf.get_feature_names_out()

# Define the number of top words to extract for each topic
n_top_words = 10
topic_keywords = {}

# Get the top words for each topic
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(nmf.components_):
    top_features_idx = topic.argsort()[-n_top_words:][::-1]
    top_features = [feature_names[i] for i in top_features_idx]
    topic_keywords[f"Topic {topic_idx}"] = top_features

# Display the top words for each topic
print("Top 10 topics for 'reviews[Nouns_adjs]': \n")
for topic, keywords in topic_keywords.items():
    print(f"{topic}: {', '.join(keywords)}")

Method 2: Gensim NMF model¶

In [161]:
from gensim.corpora import Dictionary
from gensim.models import Nmf
from gensim.matutils import Sparse2Corpus
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize

# doc2bow expects an array of unicode tokens
# we didn't clean the reviews
token_list = [word_tokenize(review) for review in review_df["Nouns_adjs"]]

# Create a dictionary representation of the documents
dictionary = Dictionary(token_list)

# Convert document into the bag-of-words (BoW) format
corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in token_list]

# Build the NMF model
nmf_gensim = Nmf(corpus=corpus, num_topics=10, 
                id2word=dictionary, # convert the word id into word itself
                random_state=0)

# Print the top 10 words for each topic
print("Top 10 topics for 'reviews[Nouns_adjs]' using Gensim model: \n")

topics = nmf_gensim.print_topics(num_words=10)

for index, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {index}: {topic}")

from gensim.models.coherencemodel import CoherenceModel
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

# create an empty list to save different coherence scores 
coherence_scores = []

for num in range(2, 15):
    # build the NMF model using the different number of topics
    nmf_gensim = Nmf(corpus=corpus, 
                       num_topics=num, 
                       id2word=dictionary, # convert the word id into word itself
                       random_state=0)
    
    coherence_model = CoherenceModel(model=nmf_gensim, texts=token_list, dictionary=dictionary, coherence='c_v')
    
    coherence_scores.append(coherence_model.get_coherence())

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(range(2, 15), coherence_scores, marker='o')
plt.title("Optimal Number of Topics for NMF Model")
plt.xlabel("Number of Topics")
plt.ylabel("Coherence Score")
plt.grid(True)

In [181]:
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image # Pillow library (PIL)
import requests
from io import BytesIO

# step 1: get the URL of the image
image_url = "https://1000logos.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Lego-logo.png" # this is an Owala logo image

# step 2: fetch the image from the website
response = requests.get(image_url)

# step 3: load the image with Pillow library (PIL)
# this provides a file-like interface for reading and writing bytes objects not a simply string
img = Image.open(BytesIO(response.content))

# step 4: convert the image to grayscale because the mask operates based on lightness values. 
# The word cloud generation process uses the mask to determine where to place words: 
# typically, words are placed in the darker areas (or the non-white areas if you invert the mask).
img = img.convert('L')

# step 5: convert the image to a numpy array
# if you are using a local image you can directly set mask = np.array(Image.open(file path))
mask = np.array(img)

# step 6: generate word cloud map with mask
wordcloud = WordCloud(relative_scaling=.1, 
                      background_color="white", 
                      mask=mask, # set up the mask parameter
                      contour_width=1, contour_color='purple' # set up the image border lines and color
                     )
wordcloud.generate_from_frequencies(tfidf_df_bigram["TF-IDF"])

# step 7: display the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
plt.imshow(wordcloud)
plt.axis("off")

(-0.5, 3839.5, 2159.5, -0.5)

Part 5: Conclusion-Business Questions¶

Distribution of Overall Ratings:¶

Most reviews are rated high, indicating customer satisfaction with the LEGO products.

Common Themes in Reviews:¶

The reviews have mostly identified LEGO sets as very good gifts for boys and use keywords like cars, bikes, sons, and grandsons. The general adjectives used are "fun," "great," and "good." From the data, there is a high tendency toward boys' products.

Dates with the Highest Reviews:¶

Specific dates like 2005-10-19, 2008-06-08, and others have a maximum of 35 reviews, likely due to Amazon's review limits per product per day.

Highest Rated LEGO Products:¶

Top-rated LEGO products include:

  1. LEGO-Jurassic-Triceratops-Velociraptor-391pcs (Rating: 5.0)
  2. LEGO-Lego-40596-Magic-Maze (Rating: 5.0)
  3. Lego-Kristoffs-Sleigh-Adventure-41066 (Rating: 5.0) #### Average Ratings Across Periods:

2005 had the lowest average ratings, likely due to limited internet access at the time and reviews skewing negative due to effortful posting. The average ratings suddenly dropped in 2024 Q3, which was contributed by the anomaly in July 2024, when ratings were as low as 1. Most Active Reviewers: The most active reviewers include "Amazon Customer" with 490 reviews and a few others who reviewed 35 products. Many customers prefer anonymity when sharing reviews.

Proportion of Positive/Negative Reviews:¶

Very Positive Reviews: 76.92% Very Negative Reviews: 1.92%

Part 6: Conclusion-NLP Analysis¶

Common Themes in Reviews:¶

  1. Reviews focus heavily on cars, Lego sets, and action-oriented items. Words like "son," "grandson," and "gift" indicate that many products are purchased for children, particularly boys, as gifts for birthdays, Christmas, and other occasions.

  2. Other common themes include building experiences ("time," "building," "cool") and quality/value of the products ("good," "price," "great").

Topic Analysis Insights:¶

  1. The result of the manual and Gensim-based topic modeling reveals that most topics have the emphasis on cars, bikes, Technic sets, and gifts. They all fall within product-specific features and purchase motivation.

  2. Gensim had further clarification of such topics as:

  • Topic 1: Lego sets for kids and general enjoyment.
  • Topic 5: Bike and minifigures often connect with action-oriented themes.
  • Topic 9: Fans and Vikings could connect with nostalgic themes or themed sets.

Best Topic Count¶

The best number of topics for the NMF model is 11, reflecting a wide variety of interests, product types, and user preferences.

General Observations on Data Bias:¶

  1. The dataset is biased toward products for boys and maintains traditional gender roles in toys, such as cars, bikes, and Vikings.
  2. Positive sentiment is dominant, with 76.92% of the reviews being very positive.

Possible Limitations:¶

  1. Repetitiveness in top themes: Many topics are similar because the dataset focuses on Lego-related products.
  2. Gender bias: Reviews seem heavily focused on products for boys, possibly underrepresenting items popular among other demographics.

Part 7: Conclusion-Visualization Graph Analysis¶

  • High TF-IDF Values: Words like "item," "expectation," "nothing," and "praise" have high TF-IDF scores, meaning they are more important.

  • Low TF-IDF Values (Mostly 0.0): Many words have a TF-IDF value of 0, indicating they are either too common across all texts or too specific, making them ineffective for differentiating reviews.

  • Impact on Wordcloud: The high number of words with TF-IDF values of 0 lowers the effectiveness of the Wordcloud diagram, making it less informative and hard to extract meaningful keywords.
